Letter from my beloved daughter-in-law who died after radical bilateral mastectomies Oct., 1966 KKM
Jan 9, 1956
Dear Great Gran,
We are enjoying the fruit you sent very much - They are beautiful oranges and very delicious.
We are all fine. I suppose Katherine has told you that we are expecting a new addition to the family the last of June. We are very happy about it of course -
The children are doing just fine in school. Sally has been going to nursery school in the mornings and just loves it. I have the mornings all to myself but seem to find plenty to do. Marvin seems to keep busy with this and that around the house on weekends too. We hope to decorate (paint) the living room and dining room this spring if possible.

Went to drugstore and bought a blank for deed. Took it to Mrs. Elizabeth Mizelle to type and notarize. She did the Old Age paper and name & Clarence witnessed it, and Mr Mizelle promised to mail it for me to Mrs. Williamson. Then we got our groceries - Cora had lots of errands and in doing them she lost a report that Mildred had left with her to see 3 different Woodmen's Circle women to check with, so she went back to the drugstore to hunt it up and Clarence brought me home - groceries $4.67. Am keeping track to see how near I come to living within my income.
Yesterday morning I heard a story during the Coffee Hour and an ad. for Ever-ready batteries, or a man whose life was saved from the attack of a grizzly bear at Yellowstone Pk. The m.c. asked for stories from others as to the merits of the Ever-ready batteries. So I bethought me of the time they saved me from being sprinkled by a skunk, and at 3 a.m. - I got up and wrote out the story and mailed it to W.DBO. Orlando when I went to the p.m. I asked them to let me know if they rec. the story. As I hadn't heard the first part of the program I don't know whether or not they offer to pay for the stories. hope they do,l and that I get some ? for it.
Also, at Mrs. Mizelles I left a blank for warranty deed for you which Elizabeth will type, etc., for me.) cooked some beet greens and had some rice I cooked this a.m. and a piece of cherry pie I bot at A.& P. They do make delicious cherry pies and for only 38 cents. Also made myself a cup of instant coffee from your jar of Maxwell House, with plenty of sugar and Carnation milk to keep myself awake in case the ladder is delivered this aft - And I'm so sleepy now I can hardly see!! It probably will keep me awake all night as that happened the time before that I tried it. Weather so mild I've had no fire of any sort today. Cora said that Larrie will not be able to go to school for 4 or 5 months, and her dog Judy is in the hospital to be put to sleep.

Friday 9 a.m. Jan 20, '56
Darling Tafera,
Have just ? this letter and while I'm waiting for Cora and Clarence to come, I'll begin my letter to you. I laughed like everything over that cartoon. Wish we had as good an artist here!
The weather modulated and has been livable without the woodstove the last 2 or 3 days. Predictions are for a return tonight, but we have no clouds today so I don't see how it can freeze soon.
I hate to admit it, but no oranges picked yet. sometimes I feel like climbing and picking them myself -- but the hospital looms up, so I don't try.
Maybe that fruit is the tangelo, now. Tangelos are abt as big as grape fruit, lemon color, few seeds and sweet. tangerines are small, thin skin so you can pull it off easily and divisions are easily eaten without a lot of juice, and they are deeper color than oranges.
Shall be very interested to know the reactions to the Three Bears after next Sunday. Wish I could see those Disney pictures. I subscribed for Marlene to have the little mag pub'd at Poukipsee (N.Y. poor spelling) of Disney's cartoons. Cora has ---- reached the p.o. got 99 cents of 3rd and book of air mail stamps. Then to bank and deposited $28.00 of the Old Age acct - am buying a new ladder 22 ft at 30 cents per to be delivered, and maybe the boys who deliver will do the picking. Cora engineered all this, and told Keller ( the man who sold the ladder) that she would pay for it if I didn't want it.

Monday, March 12, 1956.
Darling Taferu,
A lot of activities the past few days! Cora has a renter who is quite a person. A vet of W.W.I, an inspector of W.W. II, a much travelled Scotchman 78 years old, but not rugged, jolly and sociable, Mr David Hobbin (I think) has taken us to Lake Placid and to Cypress Gardens and Bok Sanctuary last Friday and yesterday. At Lake Placid we called on Mrs Seaverus for a few minutes. She was having the annual committee meeting for something, so we didn't go in. She was looking very well and she gave me a large package. We went around the town, and I went into a dry goods store and bought material for a dress. Mrs. Renfro will make it for me. I went in the morning with Cora and Clarence to market, got my dinner, then was too tired to in the afternoon. Walt Disney's African Lion is this week Friday, so hope to see it. St. Christopher is the Guardian saint of the Catholics, and Ann Mc? had a token in her car.

Dottie was making buttons of the same cloth as of trimming for Mrs. Riffle's dress. 8:50 Wed a.m.  Ironed two of the nylon curtains left of the ones Lucille sent me some time ago. The other two were in rags. Mother

4-24-'56
Darling Teferu,
[unclear]] from the Z-Donahue mixtry. You gave the right address, and I'm sure I did. should have put the z. name as well as the D. Re the phone address: I feel confident now that I have the right address, so things are all straight now.
Sorry about the Scott brother's death. Hope he was well enough to do that he left his family comfortable -- as I suppose he had one.  I shall be very glad to see the girls when they come this way. Both fine girls! The only 16 year old girl I know is Martha Renfro. She is v.p. of her Junior class, plays in the band, rides the horse in a quadrille, makes her own clothes from the instructions in Home Ec. and altogether a fine, busy girl. Don't see how she could give Maxine much attention, but maybe she could help and find others. I've put the description of the ruler I want up on a separate piece of paper for your purse. Hope he will be willing to give it to you. He has no use for it now.
